4. Data Preparation

The following preprocessing steps were completed before analysis:
• Examined the dataset structure and data types.
• Checked for missing values.
• Handled missing values in the Total Charges column.
• Standardized column names by converting them to lowercase and replacing
spaces with underscores.
• Verified duplicate records.
• Created tenure groups to facilitate customer segmentation.
These steps ensured the dataset was accurate, consistent, and ready for analysis.

5. Exploratory Data Analysis

Several exploratory analyses were conducted to understand the dataset.
These included:
• Summary statistics
• Histograms
• Boxplots
• Churn distribution analysis
• Customer segmentation
• Tenure analysis
• Contract analysis
• Payment method analysis
• Internet service analysis
Visualizations were created to communicate patterns effectively.

6. Customer Segmentation

Customers were segmented according to their tenure:
• 0–12 Months
• 13–36 Months
• 37+ Months
A doughnut chart was used to visualize the proportion of customers within each tenure
group.
This segmentation provided insight into customer lifecycle stages and retention
behavior.

7. Key Findings

The analysis produced several important insights.
• Customer Churn
Customers on month-to-month contracts experienced significantly higher churn rates
compared to customers on one-year and two-year contracts.
• Customer Tenure
Customers with shorter tenure were considerably more likely to churn than long-term
customers.
This suggests that customer retention efforts should focus on the early stages of the
customer lifecycle.
• Monthly Charges
Customers with higher monthly charges generally exhibited higher churn rates.
Pricing and perceived value may therefore influence customer retention.
• Payment Method
Customers paying through Electronic Check showed relatively higher churn rates than customers using other payment methods.
•Customer Retention
Long-term customers demonstrated lower churn rates, indicating increased loyalty over time.

8. Business Recommendations

Based on the findings, the following recommendations are proposed:
•Encourage Longer-Term Contracts
Provide incentives that encourage customers to migrate from month-to-month contracts to annual or multi-year contracts.
•
Improve Customer Onboarding
Develop customer engagement programs during the first year to reduce early churn.
•
Target High-Risk Customers
Use customer tenure, monthly charges, and contract type to identify customers who may require proactive retention campaigns.
•
Review Pricing Strategy
Evaluate pricing for customers with higher monthly charges and introduce loyalty discounts where appropriate.
•
Promote Value-Added Services
Encourage adoption of services such as Technical Support and Online Security to improve customer satisfaction and long-term retention.

